occurrenceRemarks: This site burned in May 2012. It has since become an area where Vaccinium boreale is abundant. Our household has been picking V. boreale at this site every year since 2014. We harvest ~20 L each year, and many other families pick here as well. Today I walked the area for an hour and found a single berry (photo 6). There is an almost complete absence of flowering or fruiting (photo 5). Most V. boreale plants have dead branches. Other plants also show drought stress: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/93606278
Vaccinium boreale voucher CCDB-20334-H04 5.8S ribosomal RNA gene, partial sequence internal transcribed spacer 2, complete sequence and large subunit ribosomal RNA gene, partial sequence.

identificationRemarks: Hi Marilyn! Welcome to iNaturalist! The main difference is size (leaf size, and also the stature of the plant), which can be tricky to judge on a photo. Comparing the leaves to the flowers, in V. boreale the flowers should be about as long as the leaves are wide. In V. angustifolium, the leaves are usually much wider than the flowers are long. Here's one to compare it to: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/12529886 Ty
